Adult male.description: Common Grackles are larger with a longer tail than European Starlings. They also have dark legs, a dark bill, and yellow eyes whereas starlings have pinkish legs, a yellow bill (breeding birds), and a dark eye.

Brewer's Blackbirds have a thicker and darker bill than the thin, pointed yellow bill on breeding European Starlings. Brewer's Blackbirds also do not show the intricate iridescent patterns like the starling.

Female.description: Females could be confused with juvenile European Starlings, but they have a thicker bill and a longer tail.

Breeding male.description: Rusty Blackbirds are larger and chunkier than European Starlings. They also have a yellow eye whereas European Starlings have a dark eye.

Nonbreeding male.description: Nonbreeding male Rusty Blackbirds are mottled brown and black unlike the intricate iridescent pattern of European Starlings. They also have a yellow eye whereas starlings have a dark eye.

Female (Red-winged).description: Female Red-winged Blackbirds are brown and heavily streaked unlike juvenile or nonbreeding European Starlings—juveniles are tan and unstreaked and nonbreeding birds are heavily spotted.

Adult male.description: Brown-headed Cowbirds have a thick conical bill whereas European Starlings have a thin and pointed bill.

Female.description: Female Brown-headed Cowbirds could be confused with juvenile European Starlings, but cowbirds have a thick conical bill while starlings have a long and pointed bill.
